4 A JOINT RESOLUTION OF THE SENATE AND THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE STATE OF
5 MONTANA DECLARING THAT BIOLOGICAL BOYS AND MEN SHOULD NOT BE ALLOWED TO PLAY
6 GIRLS' AND WOMEN'S SPORTS AND URGING THE UNITED STATES CONGRESS TO PASS THE
7 PROTECTION OF WOMEN AND GIRLS IN SPORTS ACT OF 2025.
8
9 WHEREAS, in 1972, the United States Congress enacted Title IX of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 for the
10 purpose of prohibiting discrimination based upon sex in any school or any other education program that
11 receives funding from the federal government; and
12 WHEREAS, Title IX gives women athletes the right to equal opportunity in sports in educational
13 institutions that receive federal funds from elementary schools to colleges and universities; and
14 WHEREAS, Title IX has made a lasting and significant impact on the lives of girls and women by
15 increasing the participation of girls and women in athletics; and
16 WHEREAS, Title IX has led to a significant increase in the number of girls participating in athletics at
17 the high school level, from less than 300,000 in 1972 to 3.5 million in 2021, while the number of women
18 participating in collegiate athletics has risen from 29,997 in 1972 to 215,486 in 2021; and
19 WHEREAS, girls and women who participate in sports are more likely to get better grades in schools
20 and are more likely to graduate than girls who do not play sports; and
21 WHEREAS, girls and women who play sports have higher levels of confidence and self-esteem and
22 improved physical and mental health; and
23 WHEREAS, girls and women who play sports develop lifelong skills, such as organization and time
24 management skills; and
25 WHEREAS, allowing biological boys and men to participate in girls' and women’s sports is unfair and
26 discriminatory because it prevents girls and women from playing sports; and
27 WHEREAS, allowing biological boys and men to participate in girls' and women’s sports prevents girls
28 and women from experiencing the benefits of sports; and
